Fe3+ with molar ratios of 10%, 20%, 30% and 40% to starting material, l-histidine, were adopted in the hydrothermal synthetic process of NCDs, correspondingly the products are named Fe10-NCDs, Fe20-NCDs, Fe30-NCDs and Fe40-NCDs. The TEM images verify that all NCDs share a quasi-spherical shape, about 4 nm in diameter, except for Fe40-NCDs (Fig. 1
                     , Fig. S1 and Table S1
                     ). Fe40-NCDs are smaller in size and more irregular in shape than the others. It is because excess Fe3+ could disturb the formation of NCDs and cause abnormal optical property. High-resolution TEM (HRTEM) reveals that both Fe-NCDs and p-NCDs have similar (102) lattice spacing of graphitic carbon of 0.21 nm (the insets of Fig. 1 and Fig. S1a) [40]. AFM shows that the prepared NCDs are about 2–4 nm tall (Fig. S2) and it can be inferred that a few interlayers exist in NCDs. The results of TEM and AFM prove that Fe3+ catalysis has no apparent influence on the growth rates and morphological characteristics of NCDs, which are sometimes considered as factors to affecting PL quality [18].

Interestingly, Fe10-NCDs can act as a type of fluorescent probe for Fe3+ at μmol L−1 level (Fig. 8
                     ). In comparison with other common metal ions, only Fe3+ can effectively quench PL of Fe10-NCDs at pH 1.2. The variation of PL intensity (I/I
                     0) has two good linear relationships versus the concentration of Fe3+ in the range of 1–10 μmol L−1 and 10–500 μmol L−1, respectively. Such a strong quenching effect is due to the coordination between Fe3+ and the surface groups of Fe10-NCDs, which generates non-radiative electron-transfer [27,50].
